# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-detection-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:network-detection-deep/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] There are multiple ways to acquire packets for deep packet inspection.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Using port mirroring (sometimes called Span Port) is a very common way, as well as physically inserting a network tap which duplicates and sends the data stream to an analyzer tool for inspection.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection (and filtering) enables advanced network management, user service, and security functions as well as Internet data mining, eavesdropping, and censorship.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Although DPI has been used for Internet management for many years, some advocates of net neutrality fear that the technique may be used anticompetitively or to reduce the openness of the Internet.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI is used in a wide range of applications, at the “enterprise level” (according to corporations and larger institutions), telecommunications service providers, and governments.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI technology has a long and technologically advanced history, starting in the 1990s, before the technology entered what is seen today as common, mainstream deployments.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Essential DPI functionality includes analysis of packet headers and protocol fields.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] For example, Wireshark offers essential DPI functionality through its numerous dissectors that display field names and content and, in some cases, offer interpretation of field values.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Some security solutions that offer DPI combine the functionality of an intrusion detection system (IDS) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS) with a traditional stateful firewall.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] This combination makes it possible to detect certain attacks that neither the IDS/IPS nor the stateful firewall can catch on their own.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Stateful firewalls, while able to see the beginning and end of a packet flow, cannot catch events on their own that would be out of bounds for a particular application.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] While IDSs are able to detect intrusions, they have very little capability in blocking such an attack.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPIs are used to prevent attacks from viruses and worms at wire speeds.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] More specifically, DPI can be effective against buffer overflow attacks, denial-of-service attacks (DoS), sophisticated intrusions, and a small percentage of worms that fit within a single packet.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI-enabled devices have the ability to look at Layer 2 and beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In some cases, DPI can be invoked to look through Layer 2-7 of the OSI model.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] This includes headers and data protocol structures as well as the payload of the message.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI functionality is invoked when a device looks or takes other action based on information beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI can identify and classify traffic based on a signature database that includes information extracted from the data part of a packet, allowing finer control than classification based only on header information.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] End points can utilize encryption and obfuscation techniques to evade DPI actions in many cases.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] A classified packet may be redirected, marked/tagged (see quality of service), blocked, rate limited, and of course, reported to a reporting agent in the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In this way, HTTP errors of different classifications may be identified and forwarded for analysis.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Many DPI devices can identify packet flows (rather than packet-by-packet analysis), allowing control actions based on accumulated flow information.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Initially security at the enterprise level was just a perimeter discipline, with a dominant philosophy of keeping unauthorized users out, and shielding authorized users from the outside world.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The most frequently used tool for accomplishing this has been a stateful firewall.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] It can permit fine-grained control of access from the outside world to pre-defined destinations on the internal network, as well as permitting access back to other hosts only if a request to the outside world has been made previously.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Vulnerabilities exist at network layers, however, that are not visible to a stateful firewall.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Firewalls also do not distinguish between permitted and forbidden uses of legitimately-accessed applications.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI enables IT administrators and security officials to set policies and enforce them at all layers, including the application and user layer to help combat those threats.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is able to detect a few kinds of buffer overflow attacks.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI may be used by enterprise for Data Leak Prevention (DLP).
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] When an e-mail user tries to send a protected file, the user may be given information on how to get the proper clearance to send the file.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI to secure their internal networks, Internet service providers (ISPs) also apply it on the public networks provided to customers.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Common uses of DPI by ISPs are lawful intercept, policy definition and enforcement, targeted advertising, quality of service, offering tiered services, and copyright enforcement.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers are required by almost all governments worldwide to enable lawful intercept capabilities.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Decades ago in a legacy telephone environment, this was met by creating a traffic access point (TAP) using an intercepting proxy server that connects to the government's surveillance equipment.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The acquisition component of this functionality may be provided in many ways, including DPI, DPI-enabled products that are "LI or CALEA-compliant" can be used – when directed by a court order – to access a user's datastream.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In some countries the ISPs are required to perform filtering, depending on the country's laws.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows service providers to "readily know the packets of information you are receiving online—from e-mail, to websites, to sharing of music, video and software downloads".
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Because ISPs route the traffic of all of their customers, they are able to monitor web-browsing habits in a very detailed way allowing them to gain information about their customers' interests, which can be used by companies specializing in targeted advertising.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] At least 100,000 United States customers are tracked this way, and as many as 10% of U.S. customers have been tracked in this way.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Technology providers include NebuAd, Front Porch, and Phorm.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs monitoring their customers include Knology and Wide Open West.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In addition, the United Kingdom ISP British Telecom has admitted testing solutions from Phorm without their customers' knowledge or consent.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Applications such as peer-to-peer (P2P) traffic present increasing problems for broadband service providers.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Typically, P2P traffic is used by applications that do file sharing.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] These may be any kind of files (i.e. documents, music, videos, or applications).
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Due to the frequently large size of media files being transferred, P2P drives increasing traffic loads, requiring additional network capacity.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers say a minority of users generate large quantities of P2P traffic and degrade performance for the majority of broadband subscribers using applications such as e-mail or Web browsing which use less bandwidth.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Poor network performance increases customer dissatisfaction and leads to a decline in service revenues.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows the operators to oversell their available bandwidth while ensuring equitable bandwidth distribution to all users by preventing network congestion.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Additionally, a higher priority can be allocated to a VoIP or video conferencing call which requires low latency versus web browsing which does not.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] This is the approach that service providers use to dynamically allocate bandwidth according to traffic that is passing through their networks.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Mobile and broadband service providers use DPI as a means to implement tiered service plans, to differentiate "walled garden" services from "value added", "all-you-can-eat" and "one-size-fits-all" data services.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs are sometimes requested by copyright owners or required by courts or official policy to help enforce copyrights.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, one of Denmark's largest ISPs, Tele2, was given a court injunction and told it must block its customers from accessing The Pirate Bay, a launching point for BitTorrent.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Instead of prosecuting file sharers one at a time, the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) and the big four record labels EMI, Sony BMG, Universal Music, and Warner Music have sued ISPs such as Eircom for not doing enough about protecting their copyrights.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), which aims to enforce movie copyrights, has taken the position with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) that network neutrality could hurt anti-piracy techniques such as deep packet inspection and other forms of filtering.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI for the security of their own networks, governments in North America, Europe, and Asia use DPI for various purposes such as surveillance and censorship.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Chinese government uses deep packet inspection to monitor and censor network traffic and content that it claims is harmful to Chinese citizens or state interests.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] This material includes pornography, information on religion, and political dissent.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Chinese network ISPs use DPI to see if there is any sensitive keyword going through their network.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] China previously blocked all VoIP traffic in and out of their country but many available VoIP applications now function in China.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Voice traffic in Skype is unaffected, although text messages are subject to filtering, and messages containing sensitive material, such as curse-words, are simply not delivered, with no notification provided to either participant in the conversation.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] China also blocks visual media sites such as YouTube.com and various photography and blogging sites.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Since 2015, Egypt reportedly started to join the list which was constantly being denied by the Egyptian National Telecom Regulatory Authority (NTRA) officials.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] However, it came to news when the country decided to block the encrypted messaging app Signal as announced by the application's developer.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In April 2017, all VoIP applications including FaceTime, Facebook Messenger, Viber, WhatsApp calls and Skype have been all blocked in the country.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] As of 2022, FaceTime, Facebook Messenger are unblocked.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Indian ISP Jio, which is also the largest network operator in India has been known to employ sophisticated DPI techniques like SNI-based filtering to enforce censorship.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Indonesian government via Telkom Indonesia, supported by Cisco Meraki DPI technology, perform country-wide surveillance by the way of deep packet inspection, and map it into SSN/NIK (Nomor Induk Kependudukan) of its citizens that registered to the state-owned ISP.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of deep packet inspection including filtering porn, hate speech, and reducing tension in West Papua.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Indonesian Government planned to scale up the surveillance to next level until 2030.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] According to unnamed experts cited in the article, the system "enables authorities to not only block communication but to monitor it to gather information about individuals, as well as alter it for disinformation purposes".
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The system was purchased by the Telecommunication Infrastructure Co., part of the Iranian government's telecom monopoly.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] According to the *Journal*, NSN "provided equipment to Iran last year under the internationally recognized concept of 'lawful intercept,' said Mr.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] That relates to intercepting data for the purposes of combating terrorism, child pornography, drug trafficking, and other criminal activities carried out online, a capability that most if not all telecom companies have, he said....
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] He said the company determined it was no longer part of its core business.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The NSN system followed on purchases by Iran from Secure Computing Corp. earlier in the decade.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Questions have been raised about the reporting reliability of the *Journal* report by David Isenberg, an independent Washington, D.C.–based analyst and Cato Institute Adjunct Scholar, specifically saying that Mr.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Roome is denying the quotes attributed to him and that he, Isenberg, also had similar complaints with one of the same *Journal* reporters in an earlier story.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] NSN has issued the following denial: NSN "has not provided any deep packet inspection, web censorship or Internet filtering capability to Iran".
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] A concurrent article in *The New York Times* stated the NSN sale had been covered in a "spate of news reports in April [2009], including *The Washington Times*," and reviewed censorship of the Internet and other media in the country, but did not mention DPI.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] According to Walid Al-Saqaf, the developer of the internet censorship circumventor Alkasir, Iran was using deep packet inspection in February 2012, bringing internet speeds in the entire country to a near standstill.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] This briefly eliminated access to tools such as Tor and Alkasir.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The incumbent Malaysian government, headed by Barisan Nasional, was said to be using DPI against a political opponent during the run-up to the 13th general elections held on 5 May 2013.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of DPI, in this instance, was to block and/or hinder access to selected websites, e.g.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Facebook accounts, blogs and news portals.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) states that the DPI system has been installed to implement the Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act (PECA) 2016, particularly to filter and block blasphemous content and any material that is considered to be against the integrity or security of Pakistan.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Canadian firm Sandvine was contracted to provide and set up the equipment in Pakistan.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Federal Law No.139 enforces blocking websites on the Russian Internet blacklist using IP filtering, but does not force ISPs into analyzing the data part of packets.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Yet some ISPs still use different DPI solutions to implement blacklisting.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] For 2019, the governmental agency Roskomnadzor is planning a nationwide rollout of DPI after the pilot project in one of the country's regions, at an estimated cost of 20 billion roubles (US$300M).
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The city state reportedly employs deep packet inspection of Internet traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] FCC adopts Internet CALEA requirements: The FCC, pursuant to its mandate from the U.S.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Congress, and in line with the policies of most countries worldwide, has required that all telecommunication providers, including Internet services, be capable of supporting the execution of a court order to provide real-time communication forensics of specified users.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, the FCC adopted new Title 47, Subpart Z, rules requiring Internet Access Providers to meet these requirements.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] DPI was one of the platforms essential to meeting this requirement and has been deployed for this purpose throughout the U.S.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The National Security Agency (NSA), with cooperation from AT&T Inc., has used deep packet inspection to make internet traffic surveillance, sorting, and forwarding more intelligent.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The DPI is used to find which packets are carrying e-mail or a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephone call.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Traffic associated with AT&T's Common Backbone was "split" between two fibers, dividing the signal so that 50 percent of the signal strength went to each output fiber.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] One of the output fibers was diverted to a secure room; the other carried communications on to AT&T's switching equipment.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The secure room contained Narus traffic analyzers and logic servers; Narus states that such devices are capable of real-time data collection (recording data for consideration) and capture at 10 gigabits per second.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Certain traffic was selected and sent over a dedicated line to a "central location" for analysis.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] According to an affidavit by expert witness J.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Narus's Semantic Traffic Analyzer software, which runs on IBM or Dell Linux servers using DPI, sorts through IP traffic at 10 Gbit/s to pick out specific messages based on a targeted e-mail address, IP address or, in the case of VoIP, telephone number.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Gonzales have asserted that they believe the president has the authority to order secret intercepts of telephone and e-mail exchanges between people inside the United States and their contacts abroad without obtaining a FISA warrant.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] The Defense Information Systems Agency has developed a sensor platform that uses deep packet inspection.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Vietnam launched its network security center and required ISPs to upgrade their hardware systems to use deep packet inspection to block Internet traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is considered by many to undermine the infrastructure of the internet.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] There is a greater emphasis being placed on deep packet inspection - this comes in light after the rejection of both the SOPA and PIPA bills.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Many current DPI methods are slow and costly, especially for high bandwidth applications.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] More efficient methods of DPI are being developed.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Specialized routers are now able to perform DPI; routers armed with a dictionary of programs will help identify the purposes behind the LAN and internet traffic they are routing.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] Cisco Systems is now on their second iteration of DPI enabled routers, with their announcement of the CISCO ISR G2 router.
[src:network-detection-deep/deep-packet-inspection] A comprehensive comparison of various network traffic classifiers, which depend on deep packet inspection (PACE, OpenDPI, 4 different configurations of L7-filter, NDPI, Libprotoident, and Cisco NBAR), is shown in the Independent Comparison of Popular DPI Tools for Traffic Classification.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:network-detection-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD is the continuous monitoring of a network for unusual events or trends.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD is an integral part of network behavior analysis (NBA), which offers security in addition to that provided by traditional anti-threat applications such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, antivirus software and spyware-detection software.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD was designed and developed by Ted B Rybicki at Hewlett-Packard (HP) Roseville CA in the HP ProCurve Networking division and was first released in the HP ProCurve Plus (PCM) of Network Management products.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] Most security monitoring systems utilize a signature-based approach to detect threats.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] They generally monitor packets on the network and look for patterns in the packets which match their database of signatures representing pre-identified known security threats.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD-based systems are particularly helpful in detecting security threat vectors in two instances where signature-based systems cannot: (i) new zero-day attacks, and (ii) when the threat traffic is encrypted such as the command and control channel for certain Botnets.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] An NBAD program tracks critical network characteristics in real time and generates an alarm if a strange event or trend is detected that could indicate the presence of a threat.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] Large-scale examples of such characteristics include traffic volume, bandwidth use and protocol use.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD solutions can also monitor the behavior of individual network subscribers.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] In order for NBAD to be optimally effective, a baseline of normal network or user behavior must be established over a period of time.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] Once certain parameters have been defined as normal, any departure from one or more of them is flagged as anomalous.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD technology/techniques are applied in a number of network and security monitoring domains including: (i) Log analysis (ii) Packet inspection systems (iii) Flow monitoring systems and (iv) Route analytics.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-behavior-anomaly-detection] NBAD has also been described as outlier detection, novelty detection, deviation detection and exception mining.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] In computer networks, **network traffic measurement** is the process of measuring the amount and type of traffic on a particular network.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] This is especially important with regard to effective bandwidth management.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] Network performance could be measured using either active or passive techniques.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] Iperf) are more intrusive but are arguably more accurate.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] Passive techniques have less network overhead and hence can run in the background to be used to trigger network management actions.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] A range of studies have been performed from various points on the Internet.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] The AMS-IX (Amsterdam Internet Exchange) is one of the world's largest Internet exchanges.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] It produces a constant supply of simple Internet statistics.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] There are also numerous academic studies that have produced a range of measurement studies on frame size distributions, TCP/UDP ratios and TCP/IP options.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] Various software tools are available to measure network traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] Some tools measure traffic by sniffing and others use SNMP, WMI or other local agents to measure bandwidth use on individual machines and routers.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] However, the latter generally do not detect the type of traffic, nor do they work for machines which are not running the necessary agent software, such as rogue machines on the network, or machines for which no compatible agent is available.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] In the latter case, inline appliances are preferred.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] These would generally 'sit' between the LAN and the LAN's exit point, generally the WAN or Internet router, and all packets leaving and entering the network would go through them.
[src:network-detection-deep/network-traffic-measurement] In most cases the appliance would operate as a bridge on the network so that it is undetectable by users.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] A **packet analyzer** (also **packet sniffer** or **network analyzer**) is a computer program or computer hardware such as a packet capture appliance that can analyze and log traffic that passes over a computer network or part of a network.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] **Packet capture** is the process of intercepting and logging traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] As data streams flow across the network, the analyzer captures each packet and, if needed, decodes the packet's raw data, showing the values of various fields in the packet, and analyzes its content according to the appropriate RFC or other specifications.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] A packet analyzer used for intercepting traffic on wireless networks is known as a **wireless analyzer**—those designed specifically for Wi-Fi networks are **Wi-Fi analyzers**.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] While a packet analyzer can also be referred to as a network analyzer or protocol analyzer, these terms can also have other meanings.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] The class of protocol analyzers can technically be a broader, more general class that includes packet analyzers and sniffers.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] However, the terms are frequently used interchangeably.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] On wired shared-medium networks, such as Ethernet, Token Ring, and FDDI, depending on the network structure (hub or switch), it may be possible to capture all traffic on the network from a single machine.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] On modern networks, traffic can be captured using a network switch using port mirroring, which mirrors all packets that pass through designated ports of the switch to another port, if the switch supports port mirroring.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] A network tap is an even more reliable solution than using a monitoring port since taps are less likely to drop packets during high traffic loads.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, traffic can be captured on one channel at a time, or by using multiple adapters, on several channels simultaneously.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] On wired broadcast and wireless LANs, to capture unicast traffic between other machines, the network adapter capturing the traffic must be in promiscuous mode.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, even if the adapter is in promiscuous mode, packets not for the service set the adapter is configured for are usually ignored.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] To see those packets, the adapter must be in monitor mode.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] No special provisions are required to capture multicast traffic to a multicast group the packet analyzer is already monitoring, or broadcast traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] When traffic is captured, either the entire contents of packets or just the headers are recorded.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Recording just headers reduces storage requirements and avoids some privacy legal issues, yet often provides sufficient information to diagnose problems.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Captured information is decoded from raw digital form into a human-readable format that lets engineers review exchanged information.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers vary in their abilities to display and analyze data.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Some packet analyzers can also generate traffic.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Such testers generate protocol-correct traffic for functional testing, and may also have the ability to deliberately introduce errors to test the device under test's ability to handle errors.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers can also be hardware-based, either in probe format or, as is increasingly common, combined with a disk array.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] These devices record packets or packet headers to a disk array.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Packet capture can be used to fulfill a warrant from a law enforcement agency to wiretap all network traffic generated by an individual.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Internet service providers and VoIP providers in the United States must comply with Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act regulations.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Using packet capture and storage, telecommunications carriers can provide the legally required secure and separate access to targeted network traffic and can use the same device for internal security purposes.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] Collecting data from a carrier system without a warrant is illegal due to laws about interception.
[src:network-detection-deep/packet-analyzer] By using end-to-end encryption, communications can be kept confidential from telecommunication carriers and legal authorities.
